Nick Scholfield is set to ride Spring Heeled in the Grand National at Aintree on April 11, after initially being expected to partner Sam Winner. Scholfield will travel to Ireland to prepare with Spring Heeled, an eight-year-old horse that won the Fulke Walwyn Kim Muir Challenge Cup at Cheltenham last year. The decision comes as trainer Paul Nicholls has not yet confirmed if Sam Winner will run in the race.
Dr. Mehmet Oz's colleagues at Columbia University criticized his TV show for promoting unsubstantiated medical advice, stating it tarnishes the university's reputation. However, they also defended his work as a doctor at the university, saying he should not be forced to resign. Instead, they suggested he add a disclaimer to his show, noting that his opinions may not be evidence-based or endorsed by Columbia.
The Duchess of Cornwall has launched her own honey brand, with proceeds going to charity. The honey is priced at £20 per jar and has received positive reviews for its delicate flavor. This launch reflects a growing demand for gourmet honey, with high-end honey sales increasing by 45% at Selfridges since last year.
Aubrey de Grey, a biomedical theorist, argues that aging is a disease that can be cured, and with the right therapies, humans could live up to 500, 1000, or even 5000 years. His theories have gained traction among Silicon Valley's elite, including Peter Thiel and Google's co-founders, who have invested in his anti-aging institute, SENS. Despite criticism from academics, de Grey believes that within two decades, technology will advance enough to repair and replace faulty genes, leading to significant lifes
Scientists from the University of Bath and Yale University have developed a new material that can generate hydrogen from water, making hydrogen fuel production less reliant on fossil fuels. The breakthrough involves a patented molecular catalyst that enhances the efficiency of water electrolysis, particularly the oxygen evolution part, reducing energy losses. This advancement could facilitate the storage of energy from renewable sources like wind and solar, making hydrogen fuel cells for cars and other applications more economical.
The Fisher-Price refrigerator magnets from the 1970s and 1980s, designed to teach children to read and spell, have been found to influence the color-letter associations in some individuals with synesthesia, a condition where senses are involuntarily joined. A study from Stanford University showed that up to 15% of synesthetes born during that period had color-letter pairings that matched the Fisher-Price magnet set. The findings suggest that while the toys did not cause synesthesia, they could influence the specific associations experienced by those predisposed to the condition.
A Texas mother, Hannah Overton, who served seven years in prison for the murder of her adopted son, will not face new murder charges after her conviction was overturned. Prosecutors have dropped all charges against her, citing multiple factors that emerged after a review of the case. Overton's family has maintained her innocence, asserting that the boy's death was due to a medical condition, not intentional poisoning.
A 91-year-old former scientist, Mary Cartwright, revisited the secret underground factory where she worked during World War II, helping to build aircraft engines. Cartwright was the only woman in her department at the Drakelow Shadow Factory in Kidderminster, Worcestershire, where she tested metal for Bristol aircraft engines between 1943 and 1945. She found it strange to see the once-bustling factory so quiet and recalled her time there as a unique experience.
The upcoming UFC featherweight bout between Chad Mendes and Ricardo Lamas could decide the next title challenger, with both fighters aiming to impress for a shot at the winner of Jose Aldo vs. Conor McGregor. Mendes, who has lost to Aldo twice, believes he is better than Lamas in all areas and hopes a dominant win will secure him another title shot. Lamas, also respectful of Mendes, expects a tough fight and is equally eager for a title opportunity with a strong performance.
An explosion at a controversial chemical plant in China's Fujian province injured six people and sparked a large fire. The plant, which produces the reportedly carcinogenic chemical paraxylene, had an oil leak that led to the blast, but no toxic chemical spill was reported. The fire is now under control, and residents nearby reported hearing the explosion and feeling slight tremors.
The MGM Grand in Las Vegas is preparing to host the highly anticipated boxing match between Floyd Mayweather and Manny Pacquiao, with an expected influx of 100,000 people. The hotel's president, Scott Sibella, has guaranteed that they will not run out of beer, unlike a previous event in 2007. Extensive security measures and crowd control strategies are being implemented to ensure the safety of all attendees.
Samantha Cameron, the wife of the British Prime Minister, made her first solo campaign appearance in the general election by visiting a UKIP stronghold, Rochester and Strood. She joined the local Conservative candidate, Kelly Tolhurst, at a special needs school, signaling the Conservatives' intent to reclaim the seat from UKIP's Mark Reckless. This visit is seen as a strategic move by the Conservatives, with Samantha Cameron expected to make more political interventions in support of her husband's re-election bid.
The shooting of unarmed black man Walter Scott by police officer Michael Slager in North Charleston, South Carolina, has sparked national outrage, but locals aren't surprised due to perceived issues within the police department. Slager's personnel file lacked indications of excessive force, yet residents claim complaints about police behavior were often dismissed. The incident highlights broader concerns about policing, including training, mindset, and legal system biases, with many in the community believing officers are not held accountable.
The Liberal Democrats expect to lose a significant number of MPs, potentially retaining only around 30 seats, due to a collapse in support. Despite this anticipated loss, they believe this number could still allow them to form a coalition government, as they are focusing their campaign efforts on a limited number of marginal seats. Nick Clegg, the party leader, is actively campaigning in these targeted seats, emphasizing the party's role in preventing the country from lurching to the political extremes.
Former QPR manager Harry Redknapp, 68, has expressed interest in returning to football management, but only at the right club, having declined a lucrative offer abroad. He resigned from QPR in February, citing knee problems and internal politics, but feels fit again after surgery. Redknapp will manage a charity football match on May 31 and is supportive of Prostate Cancer UK, having lost a friend to the disease.
The Melbourne headquarters of Moose Toys is designed to foster creativity and innovation, featuring unique spaces like a cubby-house meeting room atop a beanstalk, a basketball court, and pinball machine. Employees are encouraged to generate ideas away from their desks, with benefits such as a custom lunch room and an employee of the year award that includes a free holiday. The company, which has been in business for over 25 years and has around 100 employees in Melbourne, is known for its vibrant and playful work environment that aims to bring out the best ideas from staff.
A high-speed passenger train derailed near Split, Croatia, resulting in at least six fatalities and 45 injuries. The train was traveling from Zagreb to Split when the incident occurred around noon on Friday. Authorities have launched an investigation into the cause of the derailment.
An SBS journalist, Scott McIntyre, was fired for controversial tweets condemning Anzac Day and accusing Australian soldiers of war crimes. Geoff Winestock, a senior writer for the Australian Financial Review, defended McIntyre and labeled Anzacs as 'racist yobs,' sparking further controversy. Both the journalist and the media outlets involved faced significant public backlash for their comments.
In the first week of the election campaign, Labour received £1.6 million from unions, with the largest donation of £1 million coming from Unite. This amount was triple the donations received by the Conservatives, which totaled just over £500,000, with a quarter coming from hedge fund-linked donors. Critics argue that Labour's reliance on union funding influences its policies, while both major parties are accused of making unrealistic spending pledges.
A burglar, Joshua Sweet, who sexually assaulted a young teacher in her home, was freed by a judge after serving two months and given a three-year community sentence. The decision was criticized by a Victim Support charity worker, who argued that victims deserve justice and that the punishment should fit the crime. The victim was left traumatized, feeling vulnerable and unsafe, and had to take time off work after the incident.
The shooting of Walter Scott, an unarmed African-American man, by a white police officer in South Carolina sparked widespread outrage and grief on social media, with many celebrities expressing their condolences and anger. The incident, captured on video, showed Officer Michael Slager firing eight shots at Scott's back as he ran away, leading to Slager's murder charge. Public figures such as Michelle Williams, Janelle Monáe, and Questlove shared their reactions, with some calling for justice and an end to such incidents.
Six gay men were killed in two separate incidents in Baghdad within the past 10 days by members of their own tribes. The victims were targeted after being disowned by relatives and following tribal meetings that decided their fate. Additionally, a cafe known as a gathering spot for the gay community in Sadr City was set on fire.
A pink Hermes Birkin bag, embellished with rubies, is on sale for £140,000, potentially making it Britain's most expensive handbag. This made-to-measure bag is considered a good investment due to its exclusivity and craftsmanship. The price is equivalent to that of an Aston Martin DB9 Volante or a three-bedroom house in Nottingham.
World heavyweight boxing champion Wladimir Klitschko is deeply concerned about the ongoing conflict in his homeland, Ukraine, and the country's fight for democracy. He expressed shock and upset over the war with Russia, stating that Ukraine is suffering due to Russian aggression. Despite his upcoming title defense against Bryant Jennings, Klitschko's thoughts remain dominated by the crisis in Ukraine, where he hopes for a democratic future with the help of the international community.
Bruce Jenner's upcoming eight-episode docu-series on E! will chronicle his journey transitioning into a woman, but his children, including Kim Kardashian and sons Burt, Brandon, and Brody, have expressed concerns about him revealing too much on reality TV. They worry that the show might diminish the impact of his coming out and prefer he complete the process privately. Jenner, however, believes the series will educate people and create empathy, and remains committed to the project.
Actor Robert Downey Jr. walked out of an interview with Channel 4 News presenter Krishnan Guru-Murthy when asked about his past drug use. Downey Jr. became aggravated when the conversation turned personal, stating "I'm sorry, I really don't... what are we doing?" before exiting. This incident is not unique, as other celebrities like Naomi Campbell, Robert Pattinson, and Justin Bieber have also abruptly ended interviews due to uncomfortable questions.
A 16-year-old Syrian boy, Amjad Yaaqub, witnessed ISIS militants playing football with a severed head in the Yarmouk refugee camp after they beat him unconscious while searching for his brother. The boy's account is one of many horrific experiences reported by refugees from Yarmouk, including incidents of ISIS fighters killing children in front of their parents. The camp, once home to 160,000 people, has been largely taken over by ISIS and other extremist groups, leading to the displacement of thousands of residents.
Wigan Athletic's Martyn Waghorn was sent off for kicking Millwall's Dan Harding, leading to a 2-0 loss for Wigan, with goals from Jimmy Abdou and Magaye Gueye. The match saw three players sent off, including Wigan's Jason Pearce and Millwall's Ed Upson, as tempers flared. Millwall's win keeps their Championship relegation battle alive, closing the gap to four points, while Wigan is seven points from safety.
The majority of British workers spend around £1,840 a year on takeaway lunches, but could save up to £1,300 annually by preparing meals at home. Food website Food52 offers simple and elaborate lunch ideas, such as cheese and crackers or steamed Chinese buns, to help workers save money and eat healthier. Research shows that those who prepare food at home spend significantly less, around £552 a year, compared to those who buy lunches out.
A unique seven-day tour in Russia allows tourists to sleep in the habitat of endangered Siberian tigers for £3,500. The trip, offered by Natural World Safaris, involves setting camera traps and tracking the tigers with conservationist Alexander Batalov, although direct encounters are not guaranteed. Guests stay in basic wooden cabins within the Durminskoye Reserve, with the possibility of tigers nearby.
An Algerian jihadi, Sid Ahmed Ghlam, was arrested in Paris after accidentally shooting himself in the leg, with authorities discovering plans to attack churches and links to the murder of a young woman, Aurelie Chatelain. Ghlam had an arsenal of weapons and jihadi materials in his possession, and DNA evidence connected him to Chatelain's murder. French Interior Minister Bernard Cazeneuve confirmed that a terrorist attack was foiled and Ghlam was under surveillance prior to his arrest.
Researchers have completed the first comprehensive study of the microbiomes of an uncontacted Amazon tribe, the Yanomami, revealing the highest diversity of bacteria and genetic functions ever reported in a human group. The study shows how Western diets and lifestyles significantly impact our microbiomes and suggests that these remote communities may hold beneficial bacteria lost to modern societies due to antibiotics and limited outdoor exposure. The findings, published in Science Advances, could potentially aid in developing new medical treatments by providing insights into the natural state of human microbiomes and the factors that alter them.
The defacement of a Cecil John Rhodes statue with excrement sparked protests across South Africa against historical figures perceived as racist. Various statues and memorials, including those of British monarchs and Boer leaders, were vandalized with paint or toppled. The protests have ignited debates about South Africa's colonial past and the symbolism of these historical figures, with some groups demanding the protection of their heritage while others advocate for their removal.
An obese mother, Lizzi Crawford, decided to change her lifestyle after a child on a bus mistook her for being pregnant. She had reached 20 stone (280 lbs) due to a diet of takeaways and alcohol, but the embarrassing remark inspired her to lose over 7 stone (98 lbs). Crawford achieved her weight loss goal by cooking healthier meals and joining fitness classes, despite battling cervical cancer.
British prosecutor Nafir Afzal warns that hundreds of British teenagers idolize ISIS like pop stars, putting them at risk of radicalization. He cautions that this "jihadimania" could lead to another major terror attack unless Britain changes its approach to combating terrorism. Afzal advocates for a community-led strategy and recruiting young Muslim role models to mentor at-risk teens.
Paul Downton was sacked as managing director of the England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB) following England's poor performance in the World Cup. The decision was made unanimously by the ECB's management board, citing Downton's controversial tenure and management style. The ECB plans to create a new role, director of England cricket, focusing solely on performance, with candidates like Michael Vaughan and Andrew Strauss expressing interest.
England rugby player James Haskell dressed up as Iron Man and shared a photo on Instagram to celebrate the release of Avengers: Age of Ultron. The movie premiered in London with a star-studded cast including Robert Downey Jr. and Chris Hemsworth. Haskell, who plays for London Wasps, has had an international rugby career with stints in France, Japan, and New Zealand.
Celebrities are participating in the #SelfieEsteem campaign by sharing unfiltered selfies on social media to promote body positivity and raise awareness about self-esteem issues. The campaign, launched by Good Morning Britain, aims to address the pressure to look perfect online, with a survey finding that people take multiple selfies before posting one. Stars like Susanna Reid, Josie Gibson, and Piers Morgan have joined the initiative, encouraging others to embrace their natural appearance.
Imran Uddin, a 25-year-old student at the University of Birmingham, used keyboard spying devices to hack into university computers and alter his exam marks. He was caught after staff discovered the devices during a computer upgrade and subsequently jailed for four months after admitting to six charges under the Computer Misuse Act. The judge highlighted the seriousness of his actions, stating they could undermine public confidence in the degree system and warranted a custodial sentence as a deterrent to others.
Hillary Clinton and her husband Bill took a leisurely walk in Chappaqua, New York, while her campaign vans were serviced at a local body shop. The presidential candidate will resume her campaign trail in New Hampshire, with events scheduled for today and tomorrow. Clinton's campaign has been trying to portray her as more relatable to everyday Americans amidst criticism of being out-of-touch.
Leeds United striker Steve Morison has expressed surprise at the ongoing chaos at the club, with six players withdrawing from the squad before a match due to injuries. Former Leeds captain Trevor Cherry criticized the players, calling for their dismissal and questioning the legitimacy of their injuries. The incident is the latest in a series of turbulent events at the club, with manager Neil Redfearn's position under threat and club president Massimo Cellino currently banned.
Green party leader Natalie Bennett has distanced herself from her boyfriend Jim Jepps' controversial blog posts, which discussed topics such as 'rape fantasies' and paedophiles. The Green party has stressed that they do not endorse or want to be associated with Jepps' views, noting that he left the party in 2012. Bennett has insisted that Jepps is a "private individual not involved in party politics" and has declined to comment further on his writings.
Heather Mack, accused of murdering her mother in Bali, has agreed to turn over around half a million dollars from her trust fund to care for her newborn daughter, Stella. The funds are meant to cover the baby's urgent needs, including clothing and baby wipes. Mack's attorney filed court documents to transfer the money, stating that the baby bears no responsibility in the case.
North Charleston police are accused of attempting to cover up the shooting of Walter Scott, as initial reports did not mention Scott was shot in the back and claimed officers performed CPR, contradicting video evidence. The video also shows an officer possibly planting a Taser near Scott's body. Without the bystander video, the true circumstances surrounding Scott's death may have remained hidden.
Wayne Rooney has praised Manchester United teammate Marouane Fellaini, who has transformed from a scapegoat to a key player, describing him as one of the best in world football for his ability to bring the ball down and drive the team forward. Fellaini, who struggled in his first season, has recently been instrumental in United's wins over Manchester City and Liverpool, and is now being effectively used as a second striker by manager Louis van Gaal. United, currently on a six-game winning streak, will face Chelsea next, with Rooney expressing confidence in the team's form and preparation
The FA Cup semi-finals were held at Wembley Stadium this weekend, with the BBC and BT Sport covering the matches, despite some purists' disapproval of the venue choice. The first semi-final between Arsenal and Reading provided a thrilling atmosphere and memorable moments, including a heartbreaking error by Reading's goalkeeper. The second semi-final featured Liverpool's Steven Gerrard as the central figure, with BT Sport focusing on his potential last appearance at Wembley.
Reading, who hasn't reached the FA Cup semi-finals in 88 years, will face Arsenal at Wembley this weekend. Manager Steve Clarke has instructed his players to approach the game as a regular workday, focusing solely on winning. Despite being the underdogs, Clarke believes his team can make history by playing a 'perfect game'.
The number of new HIV infections in rural Indiana, particularly Scott and Jackson counties, has risen to 142 cases since mid-December, primarily among users of the prescription opioid Opana. The outbreak is attributed to needle sharing and the frequent injection of the drug, with the area's limited healthcare resources exacerbating the issue. Health officials, including the CDC and state leaders, are responding with education, testing, treatment, and a needle exchange program, warning that the outbreak serves as a reminder of the persistent threat of HIV and other infectious diseases.
Jeremy Clarkson will not face prosecution for his attack on a Top Gear producer, which led to his dismissal from the show, as the victim, Oisin Tymon, chose not to press charges. The incident occurred at a hotel in North Yorkshire after Clarkson was unable to get a hot meal following a day of filming. Despite his sacking, Clarkson is still set to appear in rebranded live shows with co-presenters Richard Hammond and James May.
Six U.S. Navy guards have been charged with assaulting detainees at Camp Bucca, Iraq, in May, leaving two detainees with minor injuries. The guards will face courts-martial within 30 days, while seven other cases have been resolved through nonjudicial punishment. Additionally, an incident where eight prisoners were confined overnight to a cell sprayed with riot control agent was investigated.
Dzhokhar Tsarnaev was found guilty for the Boston Marathon bombing, and jurors are now deciding his sentence: life or death. The trial's victim impact phase has begun, with heartbreaking testimonies from survivors and families of the deceased, highlighting the profound physical and emotional damage caused by Tsarnaev's actions. Prosecutors argue that Tsarnaev, who showed no remorse, should receive the death penalty for the cruel and terror-inducing nature of his crimes.
Jack Wilshere, who started at Luton Town's academy, attracted interest from top clubs like Arsenal, West Ham, and Tottenham, and made his first-team debut for Arsenal at 16. Similarly, 11-year-old Charlie Patino, a talented midfielder from Luton Town, is now being pursued by Arsenal, Chelsea, and Tottenham. Charlie's family is carefully considering the offers, wanting the best for his future in football.
A Bangkok Airways plane crashed while landing at Koh Samui airport, killing the pilot and injuring 37 people. The plane, carrying 68 passengers and four crew members, skidded and crashed after being warned of volatile winds. Seven individuals were seriously injured, and efforts were underway to free the trapped co-pilot.
Emmanuel Adebayor, Tottenham's striker, has expressed his desire to stay at the club despite reports of a potential move away, stating his happiness to fight for his place. The 31-year-old has seen limited game time this season, scoring only twice in 16 appearances, largely due to the impressive form of Harry Kane. Adebayor remains committed to fulfilling his contract at Tottenham despite criticism for some underwhelming performances.
